,Recommended,325420,23088981,"Posted: 19 May, 2016",all,Natafish,"So Homebrew.  Lets see, where to start?  Is the game good?  Yes!  Am I good with reveiws?  Absolutely not.  But how else are you gonna know it is good unless people tell you it is.  Whether or not they're good at telling you it is good.  But enough of that, on to the actual reveiw I guess.So yeah.  Homebrew...  Obviously this isn't a game about brewing moonshine in your back yard over a can of beer.  Which is kinda pointless, since you're drinking other alchohal that you payed for while making alchohal that you sell to pay for buying other alchohol, so WTF.  Anyway, we're not doing any of that in Homebrew.  In Homebrew Vehicle Sandbox, you're making your own vehicles and enjoying created vehicles within a sandbox environment.  So sorry all you moonshiners, but this is not a game about making moonshine.  Instead, Homebrew is about embracing creativity, in whatever form that may come in, and making vehicles with it.  Be it cars, trucks, planes, boats, airships, helicopters, Gundams, trains, hoverbikes, rockets, etc.  You name it and, with enough creativity and the right know-how, you can make it.  You can even sorta ""code"" videogames inside Homebrew!Homebrew does this by offering an expansive vehicle builder allowing you to combine all kinds of parts to make whatever you want.  Including a unique take on logic systems that most other vehicle building games simply don't offer.  Certainly not Space Engineers or Scrap Mechanic.Homebrew really has something in it for everyone.  If you like a certain car a lot, you can replicate it in Homebrew.  If you've got some crazy idea for a plane, you can build it in Homebrew and enjoy all that wackiness from the safety of your living room.  If you're an artist, Homebrew certainly isn't any kind of sculpting or painting software.  However, you can still make brilliant artwork by using it. Even for those fancy coding ninjas out there, I've personally made several videogames within Homebrew, including Pong and Flappy Bird, to name two popular examples.  While I'll admit there isn't currently a coding language that you use to create these games, it is in the works and will definitely be featured later on.  For the time being, it is a little clunky to code games within Homebrew, but I think I've proven it possible.Not to speak lightly of it by making it my last point, but Homebrew also has amazing developers and community.  If you're having trouble with anything related to the game, or even things not related to the game, shoot the community a question and you'll get a friendly answer fairly soon.  And if not, the devs themselves will usually come help you out!  How awesome is that?Personally, I love Homebrew.  It is no doubt my favorite game.  Granted, Homebrew has more than its fair share of bugs (at the time of writing), but those are being steadilly ironed out, and Homebrew is steadilly growing as well.  It's hard to say where Homebrew will be in 2 years.  But I can definitely say the devs are on the right track and are well on the way to making a game that pretty much everyone can enjoy.- - - - -Now I suppose I should add a few downsides (cons) as well, shouldn't I?  Well, I'm really having a lot of trouble thinking up some, but I'll give it a go.First major con:  The game has more than it's fair share of bugs.  I know I already said that pretty much word for word before, but it is worth mentioning.  Granted, none of them are really game-breaking, but they are noticeable.  There are usualy workarounds that us players can utilize, And the devs are constantly at work fixing up one bug or another.  But certain bugs have remained in the game for quite some time, and are fairly easy to spot within the first 50 hours of playing the game.Second major con:  Updates can be rather slow.  At times we've been over 2 months between updates.  While Homebrew devs are not the slowest, it can feel like it at times if you'rereallyinvested in the game.  Granted, they're always hard at work on cool new features, often times these are even features suggested by the community.  But my point still rings ever true.  The updates can be rather slow."
