76561198063892034,Recommended,325420,32428771,Posted: 15 June,all,TheGreatPotatoe,"Homebrew is one of those games that once you get going, you can't stop (evident by my 900+ hours and climbing.) Put simply: Homebrew is a vehicle builder where the only limitation is  your determination and imagination!There's definately a pretty steep learning curve concerning some of the build aspects and the logic in Homebrew. But, if you ever get stuck Homebrew has an incredible community where more than a few people are more than willing to lend a hand. Then, once you get past the learning curve Homebrew becomes this marvelous game where you can push your creativity, imagination, and knowledge to create some beautiful vehicles (or buildings) and then make it work with all the bells and whistles.When you build, it's entirely up to you when to say enough features is enough for one vehicle, from the simple forward/back, left/right car to a jet that can take off and land on its own to a rocket (or other vehicle) that can take off, fly somewhere, return and land! The best part: these are just three examples I came up with on the fly and by no means guidlines for any vehicle nor are they suggestions to how simple that vehicle might be. I.E.: that ""simple"" car I described might actually be the most complex thing you've ever built because it has active aerodynamics, steering assist, an automatic gearbox you made yourself, and so much more!In addition to Homebrew's top notch builder, you can enjoy your vehicles in multiplayer with everyone else and their vehicles! From simple car shows or ""knowledge swaps"" to races organized by the community to build contests (also organized by the community) there's very rarely no one on Homebrew's official servers.In all, Homebrew is a wonderful game that I highly recomend to anyone looking to build the cars, motorcycles, helicopters, planes, rockets, airships, boats, subs, etc. of their dreams while challenging themselves with finding the perfect s