,Recommended,325420,23088189,"Posted: 19 May, 2016",all,Field Medic,"One thing before I start is that I want to say that this game is in development by a very small team, a very dedicated and easy to talk to, but very small.That being said, those of you not familiar with the early access process should probably have taken the time to read a little bit about it before buying this game.  I have purchased many early access games on steam and while I wouldn't mind it if games had to be a bit better before being released to the public, I still enjoyed the process of just about every game I became a part of.  Some early access games I have been apart of took years to get to a playable state.  Maybe I'm just too patient.Now on to the review!As others have said, this is a sandbox building game where you can connect various pieces to make various things to drive and fly around a fairly large game area.  The build system, while a bit tricky at first, is surprisingly flexible and for those of you who know gmod/source welds, it is refreshing in how rigid the various components are and how easy it is to lift the hood and really customize things from gear ratios to fuel tank sizes.At this point in development, there are few different components ranging from small gasoline engines to vectored thrust jet engines plus all the necessary connectors and logic components needed to make them do what you want with them.  A huge selling point here is that it is not a voxel based assembly system but rather more like legos where some of the legos come in different sizes and you can even bend them to meet the way you want them to.Once you bring your creations into the world they behave more or less how you would expect them to.  The physics need work but they are quite usable and in a lot of cases the developers took the time to really get things right rather than ""cheating"" like some other games do when it comes to the calculations behind the scenes.I personally like making 6 wheeled monster trucks to drive on a tight cliff track or to try to optimize my propeller on my small scout plane so that it rotates just shy of the speed of sound to keep it at optimum efficiency.Having followed the forums a little bit, I can see that there will be some upcoming updates to physics _and_ multiplayer which is quite exciting as I can't wait to race my solar powered cars around a huge oval track or try to find and shoot down other planes that encroach on my building area.  I won't use the word potential here because you really never know, but from what I see as an armchair designer/engineer, I can't wait.In conclusion:  Don't buy this if you don't want to be in an alpha test of a physics sandbox game that changes a lot for the better.  There are other games out there in a high level of development that will satisfy your desires better...but I can say I have never found a game like this that quite captures what it is I love to do-design and test vehicles in a varied and interesting environment.  Sprinkle in some multiplayer and some exciting new parts and you're looking at an excellent addition to the world of sandbox games."
,Recommended,325420,13008825,"Posted: 19 November, 2014",all,Midi Blitz,"Probably my first very in-depth review:Updated 11/19/14This game is exactly what Minecraft, Terraria, Starbound, Starmade, Space Engineers, all of those gamescan'tbe. Even with their fancy mods and workshop items. This game is a sandbox that goes down to the pipe, to the engine, to the little motor you wouldn't think to place in a plane. It's exactly what it says on the box:Step 1, Make object.Step 2: Fly/drive/boat (soon)/etc object,Step 3: ????Step 4: Profit may vary.As a bonus, there a sort of free roam aspect to the game where you can roam around as an actual living human being instead of just an entity that inhabits the menu system. Along with that, I downloaded this getting something I didn't even expect to get: Multiplayer. I don't know how it works yet since I haven't forced this game onto a friend, but that'll change.As of this review, there've been many updates over these past seven days alone. A good sign that this is constantly being worked on.On the downside,however, this game is still taking some getting used to even now, and the controller settings really aren't optimal yet. And it's not really just the controller, but the keyboard controls sometimes either don't work, or are just weird. There's a TON of Engrish in just about every bit of dialogue (while it doesn't hinder gameplay, it does hinder game quality), and do I even lift? (An engine? Into a freaking plane without glitching the wing into the other one and forcing a tail fin onto the ground without breaking it off?).Finally, the price tag as of this moment is probably not worth it if you're into waiting for Steam Sales only to buy all of your games. Maybe at a later date when issues are fixed and a lot of things are added, sure, but until then, maybe $9.99 USD.Despite all of the bad, I still recommend it if you want more detail out of your building time."
