,Recommended,325420,13519205,"Posted: 22 December, 2014",all,[DK]Eliasr,"(STILL) Early access review (19. Nov 2016)I belive there was a fair deal of work in 2015, but it didn't peak my interest last year.This year, however there has been some changes.Phyzikov reached out to me and asked for some honest feedback on their current system to identify areas where they need to stabilize the system.First off the improvements I noticed:* An interactive tutorial to get you started with the game and understanding how to drive, sail and fly, as well as using your gadgets.* A lot of new islands that you can travel between, making the game feel less isolated.* Physics seems more stabilised.* Embedded video tutorial for building vehicles* A more lightweight interface for assembling vehicles, reducing the difficulty.* Scattered vehicles though the games are clearly marked with the glowing object and it provides a reason for the player to explore the islands.*MultiplayerIssues that needs improving:* Building isn't intuitive before the video is seen, an interactive tutorial would be good.* High speed can result in skipped collisions or rotations that goes on forever.* Surfaces that are not straight can result in wheel boots not being correctly applied.* If you swim in the deep ocean, you might risk being randomly teleport inside the center of an island under the waterlevel - in other words inside a mountain. (teleport gadgets resolves the issue)* No consequences of your actions - this can be considered good and fun, but it lacks immersion.So how would I rate this so far?The good part is that the developers are still working on the game and they seem to be doing some things actively, however sadly they have been working on this for 2 years now and is also being surpassed by other games who perhaps allow a certain amout of ""arcadic physics"".As a developer myself, I know it is really hard to model physics properly, so the challenge they are up against is a big one.My two cents would be to simplifly the physics with the aim to stabilize for playability and then add some gaming elements, so players can try completing challenges and build vehicles that are good at performing those challenges.I think it would be great to see with the multiplayer - not only because you can create content, but because you then can compete with that content - this could also be of interest for streamers.With that said, the current development seems to have focused on some different milestones than I had hoped for, and even though there are islands around me, which I think is nice, I would have prefered fewer islands and more ingame activities than building and exploring.Even though I might convince a friend to play pretend races with me and do some streaming with him, I doubt I could do it with the price tag of 17.99€, because the game itself simply lack activities or game mecanishms that challenges you to improve your vehicles.Make the most eco friendly vehicle and complete the lap.Make a solar powered plane, that is efficient enough to complete the lap without crashing.Complete a set of checkpoints (that requires a certain movability) and be the first to complete the lap.Do stunt jumps with various goals.And for the vehicle you can find when you explore the islands, it would be wonderfull if they got saved to your build projects, as a collection, making exploration even more meaningfull.I do hope the developers will look at the activites after working on stability, as it is my current main concern with the game. The improved physics over the past 2 years can clearly be felt and it is much more fun roaming around on the islands and flying planes now.I clear this review for a tiny positive recommendation, as i belive the developers are willing to put more value into the game for the customers and because a lot of the gamebreaking issues has been resolved. If you like making the most crazy vehicles and roam around in them, then go for it, and why not try the multiplayer with a friend while you are at it?While i'm a little skeptical about the pricetag, consider that buying the game from steam with its retail price, as it supports the development much better than going for a cheap key somewhere else.I leave my old review below for the sake of continuity, and because Igniuss's reply is related to that review.---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------(4 of 13 found the old review helpfull)EARLY ACCESS REVIEW ( 19 Dec. 2014)tldr: Wait for a better version before investing.I agree with this guy:http://steamcommunity.com/app/325420/discussions/0/626329820885200239/There have been some updates, which i haven't experienced from play, but just based on writing they seem to be really good.It also seem to be quite the alpha version, with a fair deal of ability to change the game design, but also a fair deal of doubt in how it will turn out to be.My experience however is that most games tend to be feature complete while in EA. It doesn't seem to be the case here, so there might be changes to all the downsides i consider for this game.1. Physics:While this game tries to cover water, land and air at the same time, i don't expect a overhelming great physics in each part, as in a simulator. However there are some parts to the physic that i consider too flawish for a game like this. Mainly how breaking and a reverse vector applied to the resulting vector seems lacking.Also using a handbrake on a slope, should not give you more speed....When it comes to flying, it is quite clear that you need to consider how you balance the weight is important. That is a plus, but unfortunately some of the engines seems to be a bit extreme and will put you in a loop regardless of your controls.2. Game loop is too simple.  (build -> test)*While The game is indeed all about building and testing, it just seems like the testing aspect could use some sub-loops to create some kind of challenge or a feeling of achivement.While removing the orbs, from what i read and would determine myself, was a really good idea. Perhaps there could be some challenges which could unlock some non essential, or bonus like content.This is one of the things i hope will be improved in the future.These issues are the ones feel is most worth mentioning, as they make the game feel incomplete or borken.The constructing part is really good and interesting, so if those issues aren't important to you, then it is worth giving it a go, especially if you can get the game at discount.There are a chance that these will be improved, but it depends on how far the development is at the current stage. Hence I suggest people to wait a bit and see if these parts get any changes to the better."
76561198038078241,Recommended,325420,20725742,"Posted: 24 January, 2016",all,Emoticons,"I think there are way more user friendly ways to build a vehicle than in Homebrew, but other sandboxes have many limits. Homebrew Vehicle Sanbox's possibilitys are almost endless even though it's still in early developement. Even simple programming with blocks is possible.You've tried stuff that was simply impossible in other sanbox games? It's possible here.The world is HUGE with bounderies very far in the distance, it already supports a nice multiplayer mode, but the build mode doesn't support multiplayer, it's currently singleplayer only.Still, the dev team delivers nice updates from time to time and the game is really progressing.On the downside:Homebrew has a finicky editor where you go a free cam and weld the things onto nodes. This isn't very intuitive yet. If you unweld parts they fall to the ground and everything attached to that unwelds as well. So you need to be thoughtful of how you want to build your vehicle.Also there is about a 5 second loading screen every time you want to test your vehicle with physics which can add up if you tune your vehicle.But it really has potential if the keep updating it.Also: If you ever need help for your build, there is a nice discord where you can get help:https://discord.gg/pyzVZgz"
